💡 Read this table first. These are all the words you need to know.

+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| WORD / CONCEPT          | WHAT IT MEANS (SIMPLE)                            |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| MLOps                   | "Machine Learning Operations." It means we take   |
|                         | a machine learning model and put it in a real     |
|                         | system that people can use. Like DevOps but for   |
|                         | ML models.                                        |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| LSTM                    | "Long Short-Term Memory." A type of brain for     |
|                         | the computer. It reads text word by word and       |
|                         | remembers what came before. Good for text tasks.  |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Classification          | Sorting things into groups. Example: you read      |
|                         | "Samsung Galaxy smartphone 128GB" and you say      |
|                         | "this is Electronics." The model does this         |
|                         | automatically.                                    |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Microservices           | Instead of one big program, we have many small     |
|                         | programs. Each one does one job. They talk to      |
|                         | each other over the network.                      |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Docker / Container      | A box that holds one program with everything it    |
|                         | needs. You can start it, stop it, move it. Our    |
|                         | project has 13 of these boxes.                    |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Docker Compose          | A tool that starts all 13 containers together      |
|                         | with one command. It knows which container needs   |
|                         | to start first.                                   |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| API (REST API)          | A way for programs to talk to each other. One      |
|                         | program sends a request (like "classify this       |
|                         | text"), the other sends back an answer.            |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| API Gateway             | The "front door" of our system. Every request      |
|                         | goes through it first. It checks who you are,     |
|                         | then sends your request to the right service.     |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Endpoint                | An address where a service listens. Example:       |
|                         | /health is an endpoint. You send a request there  |
|                         | and get back "I am healthy."                      |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Flask                   | A Python library to build web APIs. All our        |
|                         | services use Flask.                               |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Token                   | A long random text (like a password) that the      |
|                         | system gives you when you log in. You send it     |
|                         | with every request to prove who you are.          |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Bearer Token            | The token sent in the header of a request.         |
|                         | "Bearer" just means "I am carrying this token."   |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Authentication          | Checking WHO you are (login with username and      |
|                         | password).                                        |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Authorization           | Checking WHAT you can do (admin can retrain,       |
|                         | normal user cannot).                              |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Role-Based Access       | Different users have different permissions.         |
|                         | "admin" can do everything. "user" can only         |
|                         | predict.                                          |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| SHA-256                 | A way to hide passwords. We never save the real    |
|                         | password, we save a scrambled version. Nobody can |
|                         | read the original.                                |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Preprocessing           | Cleaning the text before the model reads it.       |
|                         | Remove HTML, remove numbers, remove common words  |
|                         | (stopwords), make words shorter (lemmatization).  |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Tokenization            | Turning words into numbers. The model cannot read  |
|                         | words, only numbers. "samsung" becomes 42,         |
|                         | "galaxy" becomes 17, etc.                         |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Padding                 | Making all texts the same length. If a text has    |
|                         | 5 words, we add zeros to make it 10. If it has    |
|                         | 15, we cut it to 10.                              |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Embedding               | Turning each number into a list of 128 numbers     |
|                         | that carry meaning. Similar words get similar     |
|                         | lists.                                            |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Softmax                 | The last step in the model. It gives a percent     |
|                         | for each of the 27 categories. All percents add   |
|                         | up to 100%. The highest one is the answer.        |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Epoch                   | One full pass through all training data. We train  |
|                         | for 10 epochs, so the model sees all data 10      |
|                         | times.                                            |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Batch Size              | How many examples the model looks at before         |
|                         | updating itself. 32 means it reads 32 texts,      |
|                         | learns, then reads the next 32.                   |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Loss                    | How wrong the model is. Lower = better.            |
|                         | The model tries to make this number smaller.      |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Accuracy                | How often the model is correct. Higher = better.   |
|                         | 0.80 means correct 80% of the time.              |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Confidence              | How sure the model is about its answer. 95%        |
|                         | means very sure. 30% means not sure.              |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| MLflow                  | A tool that saves every training experiment.        |
|                         | It records: what settings did we use? What was    |
|                         | the accuracy? Which model version is best?        |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Airflow                 | A tool that runs tasks in order, automatically.     |
|                         | Example: Step 1 load data, Step 2 train model,    |
|                         | Step 3 reload model. It runs them one by one.     |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| DAG                     | "Directed Acyclic Graph." A chain of tasks.        |
|                         | Task A must finish before Task B starts.           |
|                         | Airflow uses DAGs.                                |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Prometheus              | A monitoring tool. Every 15 seconds it asks each   |
|                         | service: "How many requests did you get? How      |
|                         | fast are you?" It saves all these numbers.        |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Grafana                 | A tool that makes nice charts from Prometheus       |
|                         | data. It shows dashboards with lines and colors.  |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| PromQL                  | The language Grafana uses to ask Prometheus for     |
|                         | data. Like SQL but for metrics.                   |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| DVC                     | "Data Version Control." Like Git but for big        |
|                         | files. Our data is 5.6 GB, too big for Git.       |
|                         | DVC tracks it separately.                         |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| CI/CD                   | "Continuous Integration / Continuous Delivery."     |
|                         | Every time we push code, tests run automatically. |
|                         | If tests pass, the code is ready.                 |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| GitHub Actions          | A CI/CD tool inside GitHub. It runs our tests       |
|                         | and builds our Docker images automatically.       |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Health Check            | A simple test: "Are you alive?" Every container    |
|                         | has one. Docker checks it. If a container is      |
|                         | dead, Docker restarts it.                         |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Nginx                   | A web server. It serves our HTML dashboard to      |
|                         | the browser. Very fast, very small.               |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| SQLite                  | A tiny database in one file. We use it to store    |
|                         | users and passwords.                              |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| PostgreSQL              | A big database. Airflow uses it to store its        |
|                         | task history and settings.                        |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Bridge Network          | All 13 containers share one private network.       |
|                         | They can find each other by name (like             |
|                         | "mlflow" or "data_service").                      |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| NLTK                    | A Python library for working with text.             |
|                         | We use it to split words, remove stopwords,       |
|                         | and lemmatize.                                    |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Stopwords               | Very common words like "the", "is", "and".         |
|                         | They do not help classification, so we remove     |
|                         | them. We remove French stopwords.                 |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+
| Lemmatization           | Making words shorter to their base form.            |
|                         | "running" becomes "run". "better" becomes "good". |
+-------------------------+---------------------------------------------------+


