Thank you, [Speaker A]. Now let me talk about security. This User
Management panel shows our role-based access control system. We have
two roles: admin and user. Normal users can only make predictions and
see their history. Admins can retrain models, manage users, and access
all endpoints.

[Point to the users table.]

When you log in, we check your password using SHA-256 hashing. We never
save the real password. We save a scrambled version that nobody can
read. When the password is correct, the Auth Service makes a
cryptographically secure random token. It is sixty-four hexadecimal
characters. This token must be sent as a Bearer token in the
Authorization header of every API request. When you log in again, the
old token stops working. So if someone steals your token, it becomes
useless when you log in next time.

The API Gateway checks every request. It asks the Auth Service: "Is
this token valid?" If yes, the Gateway sends the request forward. If
the request needs admin permission (like retraining or managing users),
the Gateway also checks: "Is this user an admin?"

For continuous integration, every time we push code to our repository,
GitHub Actions runs automatically. It runs flake8 to check our code
style. It runs pytest to test: data loading, text preprocessing, model
architecture, tokenizer serialization, and authentication logic. It
also checks that we did not accidentally commit large binary files.
If all tests pass, it builds Docker images for all five custom services
as a final check.

Now, what does it take to keep this system running? There are three
important areas. First, monitoring: Prometheus and Grafana give us
real-time numbers about service health, request speed, and model
performance. If prediction confidence drops or latency goes up, we
know immediately. Second, retraining: the Airflow DAG lets us retrain
on new data at any time. We can do it manually from the dashboard or
on a daily schedule. Third, reproducibility: DVC tracks our data and
pipeline steps. This means any experiment can be reproduced exactly.

