DOCKER EXPLAINED SIMPLY:

What is Docker?
  Imagine each service is a person. Each person needs:
    - A room to work in (container)
    - Tools to do their job (libraries)
    - A way to talk to others (network)

  Docker gives each service its own isolated room. If one person's
  tools break, it doesn't affect others.

What is a Dockerfile?
  A recipe for building a container. Example:

  FROM python:3.11-slim         ← Start with Python 3.11
  WORKDIR /app                  ← Make a folder called /app
  COPY requirements.txt .       ← Copy the library list
  RUN pip install -r requirements.txt  ← Install libraries
  COPY . .                      ← Copy all code
  CMD ["python", "app.py"]      ← When you start, run app.py

What is docker-compose.yml?
  Instead of starting 13 containers by hand, this file starts them all
  together. It also creates the network so they can talk to each other.


WHY WE MADE THESE ARCHITECTURE DECISIONS:

Q: Why 13 containers instead of 1 big program?
A: If one service fails, the others keep working. Also, we can update
   one service without touching the others. This is called "separation
   of concerns."

Q: Why Flask for all services?
A: Flask is simple, lightweight, and perfect for small APIs. Everyone
   knows Flask. Easy to learn, easy to debug.

Q: Why LSTM instead of a simple model?
A: Product descriptions are text. Text has order: "Samsung Galaxy phone"
   is different from "phone Galaxy Samsung." LSTM reads text in order
   and remembers context. Simple models (like Naive Bayes) don't remember
   order.

Q: Why LSTM instead of Transformer (BERT, GPT)?
A: LSTM is faster, smaller, and good enough for 27 categories. Transformers
   are powerful but overkill for this task. LSTM trains in 10 minutes,
   BERT would take hours.

Q: Why MLflow?
A: When you train 20 different models with different settings, how do you
   remember which was best? MLflow saves everything automatically: what
   settings you used, what accuracy you got, when you trained it.

Q: Why Airflow?
A: Retraining has 4 steps that must happen in order:
   1. Clean new data
   2. Train model
   3. Wait for training to finish
   4. Reload the model
   Airflow makes sure they run in order. If step 2 fails, step 3 doesn't
   start.

Q: Why Prometheus + Grafana instead of just logs?
A: Logs are text files. Hard to see patterns. Prometheus turns logs into
   numbers. Grafana turns numbers into charts. You see immediately: "Why
   is prediction service slow today?"

Q: Why SHA-256 for passwords instead of plaintext?
A: If someone hacks the database, they see:
   NOT: "password: admin123"
   BUT: "password: 8c6976e5b5410415bde908bd4dee15dfb167a9c873fc4bb8a81f6f2ab448a918"
   They cannot reverse SHA-256 to get the real password.

Q: Why JWT tokens instead of sessions?
A: With tokens, the API Gateway doesn't need to remember who is logged in.
   The token itself proves who you are. This is "stateless" — better for
   microservices.

Q: Why DVC for data instead of Git?
A: Git is for code (small files). Our data is 5.6 GB. Git would be very
   slow. DVC is designed for big files.

Q: Why Docker network instead of localhost?
A: Inside Docker, "localhost" means "this container only." To talk to
   other containers, we need a shared network. With mlops_network, every
   container can find others by name: "http://mlflow:5000"


