❓ Q1: Why did you choose a microservices architecture instead of a monolithic
      application?

💬 ANSWER:
    We chose microservices because it has three big advantages. First,
    separation of concerns: each service does one job. The training service
    only trains, the prediction service only predicts. This makes the code
    easier to understand and test. Second, independent scaling: if we get
    many prediction requests, we can start more prediction containers without
    touching the training service. Third, fault isolation: if the training
    service crashes, users can still make predictions. In a monolithic
    application, one bug can break everything.


Q2: Why did you use Docker containers instead of running everything directly
    on the server?

ANSWER:
    Docker solves three problems. First, consistency: the code runs exactly
    the same on my laptop, on the test server, and on production. No more
    "it works on my machine" problems. Second, isolation: each container has
    its own Python version and libraries. No conflicts. Third, easy deployment:
    I can send one docker-compose.yml file to anyone, and they can start the
    whole system with one command. No manual installation steps.


Q3: You have 13 containers. Isn't that too many? Why not fewer?

ANSWER:
    It looks like many, but each one has a clear purpose. Six are ML services
    (Gateway, Auth, Data, Training, Prediction, MLflow). Four are for Airflow
    (webserver, scheduler, database, init). Two are for monitoring (Prometheus,
    Grafana). One is the web UI. We need all of them for a complete MLOps
    system. If I removed any, we would lose important functionality like
    monitoring or orchestration.


Q4: How do the containers communicate with each other?

ANSWER:
    All thirteen containers share one Docker network called mlops_network.
    This is a bridge network. Inside this network, containers can find each
    other by name. For example, when the API Gateway needs to talk to the
    prediction service, it sends a request to "http://prediction_service:5003".
    Docker's DNS resolves the name to the container's IP address automatically.
    This is much better than hard-coding IP addresses.


Q5: What happens if one container crashes? Does the whole system stop?

ANSWER:
    No, the other containers keep running. Docker has health checks for each
    container. Every 30 seconds, Docker runs a health check command. If a
    container is unhealthy, Docker can restart it automatically. Also, because
    of microservices architecture, if the training service crashes, users can
    still make predictions. The system is resilient.


