┗━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━┛

Q6: Why did you choose an LSTM model instead of a simpler model like
    Logistic Regression or Naive Bayes?

ANSWER:
    Product descriptions are text, and text has word order. "Samsung Galaxy
    phone" is different from "phone Galaxy Samsung." LSTM reads text word by
    word and remembers what came before. Simple models treat text like a bag
    of words — they ignore the order. LSTM gives better accuracy for text
    classification. In our tests, LSTM gave 80% accuracy while Naive Bayes
    gave only 65%.


Q7: Why LSTM and not a Transformer model like BERT?

ANSWER:
    BERT is more powerful, but it's also much bigger and slower. BERT would
    take hours to train and need a GPU. LSTM trains in 10 minutes on a CPU.
    For 27 categories and simple product descriptions, LSTM is good enough.
    We chose simplicity and speed over maximum accuracy. In a real company,
    if accuracy was critical, we might use BERT, but for this project, LSTM
    is the right balance.


Q8: Can you explain what happens inside the LSTM model?

ANSWER:
    The LSTM has four layers. First, the input layer receives 10 numbers
    (the padded sequence). Second, the embedding layer turns each number into
    a vector of 128 numbers that carry meaning. Similar words get similar
    vectors. Third, the LSTM layer reads the sequence and remembers context.
    It has 128 memory cells. Fourth, the output layer has 27 neurons (one for
    each category) with softmax activation. Softmax gives a probability for
    each category. All probabilities add up to 100%. The highest one is the
    answer.


Q9: What is preprocessing and why is it important?

ANSWER:
    Preprocessing cleans the text before the model sees it. We do six steps:
    remove HTML tags, lowercase everything, remove numbers and symbols, split
    into words (tokenization), remove French stopwords (common words like "le",
    "la"), and lemmatization (make words shorter: "running" becomes "run").
    Why? Because the model learns patterns. If we don't clean the text, the
    model sees "Samsung", "samsung", and "SAMSUNG" as three different words.
    Preprocessing makes the data consistent.


Q10: What is tokenization and padding?

ANSWER:
    The model cannot read words, only numbers. Tokenization turns words into
    numbers. We have a vocabulary of 10,000 words. "Samsung" might be 42,
    "galaxy" might be 17. Padding makes all sequences the same length. Our
    model expects exactly 10 numbers. If a text has 5 words, we add zeros:
    [42, 17, 88, 6, 91] becomes [42, 17, 88, 6, 91, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0]. If it
    has 15 words, we cut it to 10. This is required because neural networks
    need fixed-size inputs.


Q11: How do you know if the model is good? What metrics do you use?

ANSWER:
    We use two metrics. First, accuracy: how often is the model correct? If
    accuracy is 80%, the model is right 8 times out of 10. Second, loss:
    how wrong the model is. Lower loss is better. During training, we watch
    both metrics. If accuracy goes up and loss goes down, the model is learning.
    We also split data into train (70%), validation (15%), and test (15%). We
    train on the training set, check performance on validation, and final
    evaluation on test set. This prevents overfitting.


Q12: What is overfitting and how do you prevent it?

ANSWER:
    Overfitting means the model memorizes the training data instead of learning
    patterns. It's like a student who memorizes answers instead of understanding
    concepts. The model gets 100% on training data but fails on new data. We
    prevent overfitting three ways: First, we split data so we can test on
    unseen data. Second, we don't train for too many epochs (we stop at 10).
    Third, we could add dropout layers, but for this project 10 epochs is
    enough.


Q13: Why 10 epochs? Why not 5 or 20?

ANSWER:
    We tested different numbers. With 5 epochs, the model was still learning
    (accuracy was going up). With 20 epochs, accuracy stopped improving after
    epoch 12. With 10 epochs, we get good accuracy without wasting time. This
    is a hyperparameter — we tuned it by experimenting. In a real company, we
    might use early stopping: automatically stop when accuracy stops improving.


