Q14: What does the API Gateway do exactly?

ANSWER:
    The API Gateway is the front door. Every request goes through it. It does
    three things: First, authentication: it checks your token by calling the
    Auth Service. If the token is invalid, the request is rejected immediately.
    Second, routing: it looks at the URL path and sends the request to the
    right service. "/predict" goes to prediction service, "/train" goes to
    training service. Third, it adds logging and monitoring. Every request is
    counted by Prometheus. This centralized control makes the system secure
    and observable.


Q15: How does authentication work with JWT tokens?

ANSWER:
    When you log in with username and password, the Auth Service checks the
    password using SHA-256 hash. If correct, it generates a random token (64
    hexadecimal characters). This token is sent back to the browser. The
    browser saves it in localStorage. For every request after that, the browser
    sends the token in the Authorization header as "Bearer <token>". The API
    Gateway asks the Auth Service: "Is this token valid?" If yes, the request
    continues. If no, you get a 401 Unauthorized error. When you log in again,
    the old token is deleted.


Q16: Why do you hash passwords with SHA-256?

ANSWER:
    Security. If someone hacks our database, they should not be able to read
    real passwords. SHA-256 turns "admin123" into a long random-looking string:
    "8c6976e5b5410415bde908bd4dee15dfb167a9c873fc4bb8a81f6f2ab448a918". This
    is one-way: you cannot reverse it to get the original password. When you
    log in, we hash what you typed and compare it to the stored hash. If they
    match, the password is correct. This protects user passwords even if the
    database leaks.


Q17: What is the difference between authentication and authorization?

ANSWER:
    Authentication is WHO you are. We check: username and password correct?
    Authorization is WHAT you can do. We check: does this user have permission?
    For example, both "admin" and "user" can authenticate (log in). But only
    "admin" is authorized to retrain the model or manage users. Normal users
    can only predict. We implement this with role-based access control. The
    Auth Service returns not just "token valid" but also "role: admin" or
    "role: user". The Gateway checks the role before allowing certain actions.


Q18: How does the prediction service work step by step?

ANSWER:
    When you click Classify, this happens: First, the browser sends your text
    and token to the API Gateway. Second, the Gateway checks the token with
    Auth Service. Third, the Gateway forwards the text to the prediction
    service. Fourth, the prediction service preprocesses the text (clean,
    tokenize, pad). Fifth, it passes the sequence to the LSTM model. Sixth,
    the model returns 27 probabilities. Seventh, we take the highest probability,
    map the number to a category name. Eighth, we return the result to the
    Gateway. Ninth, the Gateway returns it to the browser. Tenth, the browser
    shows the category and confidence. This all happens in less than 1 second.


Q19: Can multiple users use the prediction service at the same time?

ANSWER:
    Yes. Flask handles concurrent requests. Each request runs in its own thread.
    If 10 users send predictions at the same time, Flask queues them and
    processes them one by one (or in parallel if the server has multiple cores).
    The LSTM model is loaded once when the service starts, then shared by all
    requests. This is efficient. If traffic gets very high, we can start
    multiple prediction service containers and use a load balancer.


