Q20: What is MLflow and why do you need it?

ANSWER:
    MLflow is an experiment tracking tool. Every time we train the model, we
    want to know: What hyperparameters did we use? What accuracy did we get?
    How long did it take? Without MLflow, we would need to write this down
    manually in a spreadsheet. MLflow does it automatically. It also has a
    model registry: we can save multiple versions of the model and mark the
    best one. This is critical for reproducibility and for comparing experiments.


Q21: What information does MLflow track?

ANSWER:
    MLflow tracks three types of information. First, parameters: epochs, batch
    size, max words, max length, embedding dimension, LSTM units. Second,
    metrics: training loss, training accuracy, validation loss, validation
    accuracy. Third, artifacts: the saved model file (.h5), the tokenizer
    config, and the category mapper. It also tracks who ran the experiment,
    when, and how long it took. All of this is stored in the SQLite database
    mlflow.db.


Q22: How do you use MLflow in the training process?

ANSWER:
    In our training code, we have MLflow integration. When training starts, we
    call mlflow.start_run(). Then we log parameters with mlflow.log_param()
    and metrics with mlflow.log_metric(). We also made a custom Keras callback
    called MLflowCallback. After each epoch, it automatically logs the loss
    and accuracy to MLflow. When training finishes, we log the model artifact
    with mlflow.log_artifact(). Finally, we call mlflow.end_run(). All of this
    happens automatically — the training service just needs to run the code.


Q23: Can you compare different training runs in MLflow?

ANSWER:
    Yes. If you open the MLflow UI at http://localhost:5000, you see a table
    with all experiments. Each row is one training run. You can sort by accuracy
    to find the best model. You can click on a run to see all parameters and
    metrics. You can also compare two runs side by side: MLflow shows you
    exactly what was different. For example, "Run 1 used 10 epochs and got
    78% accuracy. Run 2 used 15 epochs and got 80% accuracy." This helps you
    understand which settings work best.


