Q24: What is Airflow and why do you use it?

ANSWER:
    Airflow is a workflow orchestration tool. It runs tasks in order automatically.
    Our retraining workflow has 4 steps: clean data, train model, wait for
    training to finish, reload the new model. These steps must run in order.
    If training fails, we should not reload the model. Airflow manages this.
    We define a DAG (Directed Acyclic Graph) that says: "Task A must finish
    before Task B starts." Airflow takes care of the scheduling and error
    handling.


Q25: What is a DAG?

ANSWER:
    DAG means Directed Acyclic Graph. Directed means the tasks have an order
    (arrows point from one task to the next). Acyclic means no loops (Task A
    cannot depend on Task B if Task B depends on Task A). In simple words, a
    DAG is a chain of tasks. Our retrain DAG has 4 tasks in a line: Task 1 →
    Task 2 → Task 3 → Task 4. Airflow runs them one by one. If any task fails,
    Airflow stops and marks the DAG as failed.


Q26: How does retraining work when admin clicks the button?

ANSWER:
    When an admin clicks "Start Retraining", this happens: First, the dashboard
    sends a request to the API Gateway. Second, the Gateway checks: is this
    user an admin? Yes. Third, the Gateway calls the Airflow REST API to
    trigger the retrain_pipeline DAG. Fourth, Airflow starts Task 1: call the
    data service to preprocess new data. Fifth, Task 2: call the training
    service to start training. The training runs in a background thread so it
    doesn't block. Sixth, Task 3: poll the training service every 10 seconds:
    "Are you done?" Wait up to 1 hour. Seventh, Task 4: call the prediction
    service to reload the model from disk. Done. The whole process is automatic.


Q27: What happens if training fails in the middle?

ANSWER:
    Airflow detects the failure and stops the DAG. The later tasks don't run.
    For example, if training fails at epoch 5, Task 3 (wait for completion)
    will see the error. Airflow marks Task 3 as failed and stops. Task 4 (reload
    model) does not run. This is safe: the old model stays loaded in the
    prediction service. In the Airflow UI, you can see the error message and
    retry the DAG manually after fixing the problem.


