Q32: Why do you use DVC instead of putting data in Git?

ANSWER:
    Our data is 5.6 gigabytes. Git is designed for code (small text files).
    If we put 5.6 GB in Git, the repository would be huge and slow. Every
    clone would download all the data, even if you just want to look at the
    code. DVC is designed for big files. It stores only a small metadata file
    in Git (data.dvc, 200 bytes). The actual data is stored separately (on a
    server or cloud storage). This keeps the Git repository small and fast.


Q33: How does DVC track the data pipeline?

ANSWER:
    DVC has a file called dvc.yaml that defines the pipeline. It has three
    stages: data_import, preprocess, and train. For each stage, DVC knows:
    what command to run, what files are inputs, what files are outputs. When
    you run "dvc repro", DVC checks: did the input files change? If yes, run
    the stage again. If no, skip it (use cached result). This is like Make but
    for data. It saves time: if data didn't change, we don't need to preprocess
    again.


Q34: Where does the data come from?

ANSWER:
    The data comes from Kaggle. It's the Rakuten dataset: product descriptions
    in French with 27 categories. The dataset has two parts: a CSV file with
    text descriptions and category labels, and image files (one image per
    product). In total, 5.6 GB. We use only the text data for this project.
    The images are in the dataset but we don't use them (we could build an
    image classifier in the future).


