Q35: What is CI/CD and why is it important?

ANSWER:
    CI/CD means Continuous Integration and Continuous Delivery. Continuous
    Integration means every time we push code, tests run automatically. If
    tests fail, we know immediately. Continuous Delivery means the code is
    always ready to deploy. For this project, we use GitHub Actions. Every
    push triggers the workflow: run flake8 (check code style), run pytest
    (run tests), build Docker images (make sure they build without errors).
    If all steps pass, the code is good. This prevents bugs from reaching
    production.


Q36: What tests do you run in CI/CD?

ANSWER:
    We have two types of checks. First, linting with flake8: this checks Python
    code style (no syntax errors, no unused imports, no undefined variables).
    Second, unit tests with pytest: we test data loading, text preprocessing,
    tokenizer serialization, model architecture, and authentication logic. We
    also check that no large binary files were committed by mistake. All tests
    must pass before we merge code. This is quality control.


Q37: What is flake8?

ANSWER:
    Flake8 is a tool that checks Python code for style errors and potential
    bugs. It looks for things like: syntax errors (you forgot a colon),
    undefined variables (you used a variable before defining it), unused
    imports (you imported a library but never used it), lines that are too
    long (over 127 characters). Flake8 helps keep code clean and consistent.
    All team members follow the same style.


