Q41: What if the prediction service crashes during a prediction?

ANSWER:
    The user gets an error message. The API Gateway will try to connect to the
    prediction service and get a connection error. It returns HTTP 503 Service
    Unavailable to the browser. Docker's health check detects that the
    prediction service is down and restarts it automatically (usually in 10-30
    seconds). Meanwhile, other users also cannot predict, but training and
    monitoring still work. After the restart, predictions work again. This is
    fault isolation.


Q42: What if you want to add a new category (category 28)?

ANSWER:
    We would need to retrain the model completely. The output layer has 27
    neurons (one per category). To add category 28, we need 28 neurons. This
    means changing the model architecture. Steps: First, add the new category
    to the data. Second, update the mapper.pkl file to include category 28.
    Third, change the model code to use num_classes=28 instead of 27. Fourth,
    retrain the model from scratch. Fifth, deploy the new model. The old model
    cannot handle 28 categories without retraining.


Q43: What if training takes too long (more than 1 hour)?

ANSWER:
    The Airflow DAG has a timeout: it waits maximum 1 hour for training to
    finish. If training is not done after 1 hour, Airflow marks the task as
    failed. To fix this, we have two options. First, increase the timeout in
    the DAG configuration. Second, use a more powerful server or a GPU to make
    training faster. For this project, 10 epochs take about 10 minutes, so
    1 hour is more than enough.


Q44: How would you deploy this system to production (real company)?

ANSWER:
    We would need to change several things. First, use HTTPS instead of HTTP
    for security. Second, use a cloud database (PostgreSQL on AWS) instead of
    SQLite. Third, add token expiration (tokens expire after 1 hour). Fourth,
    use a load balancer to distribute traffic across multiple prediction service
    containers. Fifth, use cloud storage (S3) for DVC data. Sixth, set up
    monitoring alerts (send email if a service fails). Seventh, use Kubernetes
    instead of docker-compose for better orchestration. Eighth, add logging
    to a central system (like ELK stack). This project has the foundation; we
    would just make it production-ready.


Q45: What if two admins start retraining at the same time?

ANSWER:
    Airflow allows only one instance of a DAG to run at a time by default. If
    Admin 1 starts retraining, the DAG is marked as "running". If Admin 2
    clicks the button while the DAG is still running, Airflow rejects the
    second request and says "DAG is already running". This prevents conflicts.
    Admin 2 would need to wait until the first training finishes. We could
    change this behavior, but for retraining, sequential is safer.


